        <!-- Section: Tax Time Bomb -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-myBlue mb-6">The Second Catastrophe: The Tax Time Bomb</h2>
            
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Let's say you win. You successfully save $1 Million in your 401(k).
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                You don't have $1 Million.
                You have a $1 Million problem.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Your <strong>Traditional 401(k) or Traditional IRA</strong> is a <strong>tax-deferred</strong> account. This is a partnership with the government. You saved on taxes up front, but you will pay them on <em>everything</em> you pull out.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                (Note: <strong>Roth IRAs and Roth 401(k)s</strong> work differently—you pay taxes up front, and withdrawals in retirement are tax-free. But you're still betting that your current tax rate is higher than your future rate. And many high earners don't qualify for Roth IRA contributions due to income limits.)
            </p>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                And with national debt soaring, do you believe tax rates will be lower in 10, 15, or 20 years?
            </p>

            <!-- Historical Tax Rate Chart -->
            <div class="my-10 p-6 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg border border-gray-300">
                <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Average Federal Income Tax Rate for Middle-Income Americans (1955-2025)</h3>
                <div class="mb-6">
